{"title_page": "Melissa James Gibson", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer\n| name        = Melissa James Gibson\n| birth_date  =\n| birth_place = [[Ottawa, Canada]]\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| occupation  = Playwright\n| residence   = New York, United States\n| education   = she went to school. You know school, the place you learn!!\n| website     = \n}}\n\n'''Melissa James Gibson''' is a Canadian-born [[playwright]] based in New York.\n\n==Life==\nThe child of former [[British Columbia Liberal Party|BC Liberal]] [[Member of the Legislative Assembly|MLA]] [[Gordon Gibson]] and journalist Valerie Gibson, Melissa James Gibson grew up in North Vancouver.<ref name=TP>[https://theprovince.com/entertainment/This+perfect+return+Vancouver+born+playwright/4066326/story.html Theprovince.com]{{dead link|date=May 2013}}</ref> She graduated from [[Columbia University]] and from the [[Yale School of Drama]] with an M.F.A. in Playwriting. After graduating, she worked as a college counselor at the exclusive arts-oriented [[Saint Ann's School (Brooklyn)|Saint Ann's School]] in [[Brooklyn Heights]], where her daughter, Celia Frey, graduated in 2017 and her son, Griffin Frey, is a current sophomore. <ref>Del Signore, John. [https://web.archive.org/web/20171106035447/http://gothamist.com/2012/12/26/melissa_james_gibson_interview.php \"Playwright Melissa James Gibson Discusses ''What Rhymes With America''\"], ''[[Gothamist]]'', December 26, 2012. \"I was a college counselor for many years at a private school in Brooklyn, St. Ann's. It's a wonderful school, really cool school. I was there pretty much since graduate school, other than two fellowship years.\"</ref>  She is working on commissions for the [[La Jolla Playhouse]] and The Adirondack Theatre Festival. She has received fellowships from the Jerome Foundation and the [[MacDowell Colony]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newdramatists.org/melissa_james_gibson.htm# |title=Alumni Playwrights |publisher=New Dramatists |accessdate=2013-05-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090902135143/http://www.newdramatists.org/melissa_james_gibson.htm |archivedate=September 2, 2009}}</ref>\n[[The New York Times]] theatre critic [[Charles Isherwood]] wrote that, with her play ''This'', Gibson \u201cgraduates into the theatrical big leagues with this beautifully conceived, confidently executed and wholly accessible work.\u201d\n<ref name=TP/>\n\n==Awards==\n* 2002 [[Obie Award|Obie]] for playwriting, Kesselring Prize, The Best Plays of 2001\u201302 for ''[sic] ''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/obies/search |title=New York Search Obies Theater Awards |publisher=Villagevoice.com |date=2012-10-17 |accessdate=2013-05-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130530010535/http://www.villagevoice.com/obies/search/ |archivedate=2013-05-30 }}</ref>\n* 2002 [[Whiting Awards|Whiting Award]] <ref>{{cite web|title=2002 Winner in Drama|url=http://www.whiting.org/awards/winners/melissa-james-gibson#/|website=whiting.or|publisher=Whiting Foundation}}</ref>\n* 2011 [http://broadwayworld.com/article/BWW-TV-2011-Steinberg-Playwrights-Awards-Honors-Melissa-James-Gibson-and-Lisa-DAmour-Inside-the-Event-20111115 Steinberg Playwright Award]\n\n==Works==\n* ''God's Paws'' (1993).\n* ''Six Fugues'' (1995).\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=NAjEKscAyCIC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Melissa+James+Gibson&cd=1#v=onepage&q=&f=false ''&#91;sic&#93;''], [[Steppenwolf Theatre Company]] commission, New York Premiere: [[Soho Rep]] (2001).\n* ''Suitcase, or Those That Resemble Flies From A Distance'' (NEA/ TCG Theatre Residency Program), [[Soho Rep]] (2004).\n* ''Brooklyn Bridge'', music by Barbara Brousal (The Children's Theater Company/New Dramatists Playground program commission) (2005).\n* ''Current Nobody'', Woolly Mammoth Theatre Company, DC, (2007).\n* ''Nuda Veritas'', Philadelphia Fringe Festival (2009).\n* ''This'', [[Playwrights Horizons]], (2009).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theatermania.com/off-broadway/news/12-2009/melissa-james-gibsons-this-extends-at-playwrights_23380.html |title=Melissa James Gibson's This Extends at Playwrights Horizons Through January 3 \u2013 Theater News \u2013 Dec 7, 2009 |publisher=Theatermania.com |date=2009-12-07 |accessdate=2013-05-22}}</ref> Canadian Premiere: [[Vancouver Playhouse Theatre Company|Vancouver Playhouse]], January 2011, directed by Amiel Gladstone.\n* ''What Rhymes With America'', [[Atlantic Theater Company]] (2012).\n* Various episodes for the TV series [[The Americans]] (2013-2014).\n* ''Placebo'', [[Playwrights Horizons]] (2015).\n* ''Given Fish'' (Steppenwolf Theatre Company commission, grants from the New York State Council on the Arts and the Greenwall Foundation)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.doollee.com/PlaywrightsG/gibson-melissa-james.html \"Melissa James Gibson\", ''doollee']\n*[http://playwrightsfoundation.blogspot.com/2008/11/interview-with-melissa-james-gibson.html \"Interview with Melissa James Gibson\", ''Playwrights Foundation'', November 11, 2008]\n*[http://www.observer.com/node/48769 \"Melissa James Gibson: Lady of the Flies\", ''The New York Observer'', John Heilpern, February 8, 2004]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gibson, Melissa James}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Yale School of Drama alumni]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Obie Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer\n| name        = Melissa James Gibson\n| birth_date  =\n| birth_place = [[Ottawa, Canada]]\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| occupation  = Playwright\n| residence   = New York, United States\n| education   = \n| website     = \n}}\n\n'''Melissa James Gibson''' is a Canadian-born [[playwright]] based in New York.\n\n==Life==